**Version Used**: master as of 10th march

**Steps to Reproduce**:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

namespace ConsoleApp7
{
    class Program
    {
        static async Task Main(string[] args)
        {
            var a = new A();
            a.B.x = await Write();
            async Task<int> Write()
            {
                Console.WriteLine("Hello World!");
                return 5;
            }
        }
    }

    class A
    {
        public B B => throw new Exception();
    }

    class B
    {
        public int x;
    }
}
```

**Expected Behavior**: No output before exception is thrown 

**Actual Behavior**: Prints "Hello World" before throwing exception

This is a follow up to https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/issues/42738 and #42464

However in those cases the lack of LTR semantics has a reason, namely not being able to pass a ref across an async boundary. Here it is trivial to preserve the semantics, by lowering Main to:

```csharp
        static async Task Main(string[] args)
        {
            var a = new A();
            var temp = a.B;
            var tempResult = await Write();
            temp.x = tempResult;
            async Task<int> Write()
            {
                Console.WriteLine("Hello World!");
                return 5;
            }
        }
```

